Bob:

Our issues with hedge funds are somewhat complicated.  The threshold issue i=
s=20
that they are severely limited by their fundamental documents (the prospectu=
s=20
will spell out what they can invest in) so we have to review those documents=
=20
before trading.  That is more than we do for run-of-the-mill domestic=20
corporates and takes a lot  of legal resources that so far have been spent=20
elsewhere.

The other issue is more difficult because it is hard to peg down and relates=
=20
to regulatory uncertainty.  About a year ago a major hedge fund (Long Term=20
Capital) got into serious trouble and the regulators stepped in,=20
orchestrating a bail-out.  There was much wringing of hands and gnashing of=20
teeth in Washington afterwards and since then there have been a variety of=20
messages coming out of Washington relating to derivatives trading with hedge=
=20
funds - none of them good.  Our view is that the regulators will be paying=20
much closer attention to hedge fund trading of derivatives than in the past=20
and we don't want that spotlight shining on us.  [In case you're interested:=
=20
notwithstanding their name, hedge funds are speculators.  Much of the federa=
l=20
regulation of derivatives has assumed that hedging -- as opposed to=20
speculation -- was safer and therefore more palatable.  The failure of a=20
large hedge fund might result in damaging ripple effects throughout the=20
financial markets.  Hence the regulators' heightened scrutiny.]

For both of these reasons, when EnronOnline was launched it was with the=20
internally stated policy that we would not give access to hedge funds (or=20
individuals - for similar reasons). =20

Commodity Trading Advisors can not trade on EnronOnline on behalf of their=20
customers just as Brokers cannot.

